{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639643"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:07:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:07:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17786"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17786"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10500"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76219"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10500"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17786"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61723"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2457"},{"type":"tags","id":"3943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4625"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24502"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24506"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76219"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset of paralysis. He has a medical history of hypertension and hyperlipidaemia. He does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 150/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals quadriplegia and anarthria, but normal eye movements to command. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Locked-in syndrome","Botulism","Coma","Persistent vegetative state","Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with quadriplegia and anarthria, but is able to communicate through eye movements, which is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Elocked-in syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. It results from damage to the brainstem, particularly the ventral pons. In this case, the patient\u0027s imaging revealed bilateral pontine infarcts. Damage to the ventral pons affecting the corticospinal and corticobulbar tracts, while sparing the reticular activating system, thus preserving consciousness and cognitive function.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBotulism\u003C/strong\u003E, a result of exposure to the botulin toxin produced by Clostridium botulinum, is characterised by descending paralysis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComa\u003C/strong\u003E involves a state of unconsciousness with no response to external stimuli, which is inconsistent with the patient\u0027s ability to communicate through eye movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPersistent vegetative state\u003C/strong\u003E involves wakefulness without awareness, where patients do not have purposeful responses, unlike this patient who can communicate through eye movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGuillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy that causes ascending paralysis, but it does not typically affect eye movements or cause anarthria in the same manner as locked-in syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Locked-in syndrome is characterised by quadriplegia and anarthria with preserved consciousness and cognitive function.","Bilateral pontine infarcts can lead to locked-in syndrome due to damage to the corticospinal and corticobulbar tracts.","The most common cause of locked-in syndrome is brainstem stroke"],"references":["Das JM, Anosike K, Asuncion RMD. Locked-in Syndrome. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32644452.","Halan T, Ortiz JF, Reddy D, Altamimi A, Ajibowo AO, Fabara SP. Locked-In Syndrome: A Systematic Review of Long-Term Management and Prognosis. Cureus. 2021 Jul 29;13(7):e16727. doi: 10.7759/cureus.16727. PMID: 34471579; PMCID: PMC8402869.","Schnetzer L, McCoy M, Bergmann J, Kunz A, Leis S, Trinka E. Locked-in syndrome revisited. Ther Adv Neurol Disord. 2023 Mar 29;16:17562864231160873. doi: 10.1177/17562864231160873. PMID: 37006459; PMCID: PMC10064471."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61723"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17786"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61723"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T14:21:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T14:22:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10500"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76219"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id